

The structures of Windows and Linux


Windows:

The systems use the identify words, for example, (C:\, D.)
The structure of a hierarchy with folders and sub-folders.
Paths use the backslash (\) to separate folders, for example: C:\Users\Name.
It has different specialist folders with "Program Files", "Users", and "Windows".


Linux:

The systems use Unified files with a single root (/).
Everything is down in the root, without drive letters.
Paths use the forward slash (/) to separate directories, for example: /home/user/documents.
Standard folders include /home (users), /etc (settings), /var (variable data).


Both systems' organization files and folders, but Linux has a uniform structure and a permission-based system.
While Windows uses separate units and a more user-oriented structure.


